Resposta_Gerada:
Para uma DFT ortonormal de 3 pontos, a matriz de transformação direta \( \mathbf{A} \) e sua inversa (conjugada transposta) \( \mathbf{A}^H \) são dadas por:

Seja \( \omega = e^{-j 2\pi/3} \). Então:

\[
\mathbf{A} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & \omega & \omega^2 \\
1 & \omega^2 & \omega
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\[
\mathbf{A}^H = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & \omega^2 & \omega \\
1 & \omega & \omega^2
\end{bmatrix}
\]

Substituindo os valores numéricos de \( \omega \) e \( \omega^2 \):
\[
\omega = -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, \quad 
\omega^2 = -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\]

As matrizes tornam-se:

\[
\mathbf{A} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\[
\mathbf{A}^H = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

Pergunta:
Is the matrix $\bA =
    \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & -5 \\
    3 & 4 \\
    \end{bmatrix}
$ unitary? Design a unitary matrix $\bB$ that is similar to $\bA$ in the sense that its first basis (column) is a vector in the same direction as $[1,~3]^T$.

Resposta_Gerada:
The forward and inverse matrices for a 3-point orthonormal DFT are unitary matrices built from the 3rd roots of unity.

Let \(W_3 = e^{-j\frac{2\pi}{3}} = -\frac{1}{2} - j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\) and \(W_3^2 = e^{-j\frac{4\pi}{3}} = e^{j\frac{2\pi}{3}} = -\frac{1}{2} + j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\).

The forward orthonormal DFT matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) is:
\[
\mathbf{A} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & W_3 & W_3^2 \\
1 & W_3^2 & W_3
\end{bmatrix}
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2}-j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}+j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2}+j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}-j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

The inverse orthonormal DFT matrix \(\mathbf{A}^H\) (the conjugate transpose) is:
\[
\mathbf{A}^H = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & W_3^2 & W_3 \\
1 & W_3 & W_3^2
\end{bmatrix}
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2}+j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}-j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
1 & -\frac{1}{2}-j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}+j\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

These matrices satisfy \(\mathbf{A}^H\mathbf{A} = \mathbf{I}\), making the transform unitary.

The outputs of the causal system \(H(s) = \frac{1}{s+10}\) for each input are found using the property that for an LTI system, an input \(e^{s_0 t}\) produces an output \(H(s_0) e^{s_0 t}\), provided \(s_0\) lies in the region of convergence. The ROC is \(\operatorname{Re}\{s\} > -10\), which includes all given signals.

\[
\begin{aligned}
y_1(t) &= H(j4) e^{j4t} = \frac{1}{10 + j4} e^{j4t} = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{29}} e^{j(4t - \arctan 0.4)} \\
y_2(t) &= H(-j4) e^{-j4t} = \frac{1}{10 - j4} e^{-j4t} = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{29}} e^{-j(4t - \arctan 0.4)} \\
y_3(t) &= \mathcal{Re}\{y_1(t)\} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{116}} \cos(4t - \arctan 0.4) = \frac{10\cos 4t + 4\sin 4t}{116} = \frac{5\cos 4t + 2\sin 4t}{58} \\
y_4(t) &= H(-1+j4) e^{(-1+j4)t} = \frac{1}{9 + j4} e^{(-1+j4)t} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{97}} e^{-t} e^{j(4t - \arctan \frac{4}{9})}
\end{aligned}
\]
